## Auditing How This Knowledge Base Changed

This directory does not keep its own changelog file — that would duplicate
git history, which the philosophy above already tells you to avoid. Git
history *is* the changelog:

- How one doc evolved: `git log --follow -p -- docs/ai/<file>.md`
- Everything that's happened to the knowledge base: `git log --oneline -- docs/ai/`

Write commit messages for `docs/ai/` changes the same way you would for
code — they're the only record of *when* and *why* a doc changed, since the
docs themselves only hold present-tense truth.

## Relationship to Local Memory

Some AI tools (e.g. Claude Code's auto-memory) also persist information
between sessions, but that memory is local to one machine/user and
invisible to sessions running elsewhere (another machine, a teammate's
agent, a cloud sandbox). Anything durable enough to matter across machines
belongs here, in the repo, not only in local memory.
